title: For Sale:  16" Carbine Length AR15 5.45x39 Medium
postcontent:
A 16" carbine length AR15 chambered in 5.45x39. 
The upper was built from a Daniel Defense standard ar15 upper receiver with m4 feedramps. 16" Medium contour barrel, hard chromed chamber and bore 1:8 twist. Standard F stamped FSB. CMMG bolt carrier with Alexander Arms 5.45 bolt, extrasize gas rings and BCM SOPMOD extractor upgrade with extra strength extractor spring, harder insert and oring etc. Standard M4 handguards. Standard A2 flash hider. Standard AR charging handle. For lubrication I have only used slip 2000 EWL and phil wood grease for the bolt lugs and gas rings. Barrel nut torqued at 60 ft lbs. Proper headspace etc. Front sight base is actually only a few clicks away from top dead center which is great for a standard FSB. (My BCMs are many clicks but still within milspec). Only ever fired Silver Bear from this rifle, I save the corrosive surplus ammo for my beater. Although from personal experience using lacquered cased/berdan primed ammunition is okay if you clean your rifle. Every round fired from this rifle came from the same case of silver bear, which still looks to be about half full so it hasn't seen many rounds maybe 500 *just look at the brass deflector. 

The lower half is a CMMG standard lower receiver. I tried a couple receivers when building to make sure it fits snug with upper receiver. Standard milspec parts kit with a Wolf Extra power hammer spring for the hard primers you see on most 5.45 ammo. An end plate sling adapter so you can run a single point sling from the end of the receiver. Palmetto State Armory H buffer and buffer spring.  Magpul MOE pistol grip. Magpul enhanced trigger guard. Standard collapsible stock.

I really don't want to get rid of this rifle and I have been putting it off for months now making up excuses, but I need the money to get laser tattoo removal. Understand if you buy this you are buying a rifle chambered in 5.45x39 NOT 5.56x45. It is a soviet caliber designed to copy the standard cartridge our military used in the older M16s. The whole point of this build is to shoot thousands of rounds for cheap while using the same platform as your main rifle. It feels/sounds exactly the same as .223/5.56 and has the same ballistics so you don't have to use a different zero or ballistic reticle than your 5.56 rifle. Just zero at 50 meters or 36 yards or whatever you normally zero at, and enjoy shooting 1080 rounds for 130-160 bucks.  I have found that poa/poi (62g fmj silver bear) matches 77g 5.56 at 100 meters, shooting a little lower than 62g 5.56 probably because of slightly lower pressure and velocities from that particular cartridge, but is more accurate beyond 200 meters comparable to heavier OTM rounds. I can include a handful of mags including a pmag modified for 5.45. Message me and we can figure out when and where to do this.

title: For Sale:  Rem 870 Wingmaster 20ga Lwt Barrel 28" Mod
postcontent:
Remington 870 Wingmaster 20ga Lightweight Barrel. 28" Fixed Modified choke, Vent Rib, 3" Chamber. Steel front bead.

This barrel is in unfired and excellent condition, a few VERY minor marks are present, probably from rattling around in the box over the years. In fact, I had to clean off the petrified factory preservative for the photos (after I cut the original factory tape on the box to open it). You aren't likely to find one in better condition.

OEM box is included with the barrel.

This barrel has the high-gloss Wingmaster finish, NOT the lower end Express finish.

This barrel is for the "lightweight" actions, 1972 to current mfg. If the serial number on your receiver ends in "X" or "N", then this barrel WILL NOT fit your gun. If it ends with anything else, then it WILL fit your gun.

As a secondary check, if a quarter WILL NOT fit through the barrel band (the part that goes around the magazine tube) of your existing barrel, then this barrel WILL fit on your gun. If a quarter WILL fit through the barrel band (meaning you have a full size/standardweight) of your existing barrel, then this barrel WILL NOT fit your gun.

This barrel WILL fit in the 870 Express Magnum 20ga guns, and would be a nice way to dress up your gun.

If you have a receiver/action stamped "Magnum", then you can shoot 3" shells through your gun with this barrel. If your receiver is NOT stamped "Magnum" then you are limited to 2 3/4" shells, since your action is not set up for magnum shells.

Like all polytech AKs, this rifle has run flawlessly and has the smoothest bolt and action of any AK I've ever held. KelTec P-3AT compact pistol chambered in .380 ACP. The P-3AT is a semi-automatic, locked breech pistol, chambered for the .380 Auto cartridge. title: For Sale:  M44 Mosin-Nagant Carbine, 7.62x54r excellent condition with accessories
postcontent:
I have for sale an M44 Mosin carbine, the rifle is a 1946 manufacture Izhevsk and is in extremely good condition. The flaking shellac on the stock was removed and replaced with a rubbed linseed-oil finish, which according to my research is what most Mosins apparently had prior to their rearsenal and and preparation for long-term storage in the 1950s and 60s.

The bluing on the barrel, receiver, and bayonet appear to be original and fully-intact and unlike some importer engravings this rifle bears only a small faint roll-mark on the barrel by the bayonet. The bolt is mostly still shiny but has darkened with use somewhat around the bolt handle. As you can see in the pictures the bore is bright, sharp, and shiny with no pitting or corrosion.

The rifle has been fully de-cosmolined and comes with several accessories- a bolt cleaning tool, muzzle cleaning rod guide, spare stock recoil bolt, a two-compartment oil can, two spare ejectors, a bolt cocking peice, cleaning rod, and a period-correct dog-collar style canvas sling.

I live in Lincoln County, MO about 50 miles north of St. Louis. If you're coming from STL I would be willing to meet you in the middle at a public place somewhere in St. Charles county for a FTF transfer, such as Bass Pro or Cabelas.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Walther Umarex H&K HK 416 D .22lr Tactical AR Style Carbine Trade For Masterpiece 9mm Pistol Or?
postcontent:
Wife bought this for me on Valentines day last year for about $640 from big 5. Nothing says love like a deadly weapon. Took it camping a few times and have fired exactly 60 rounds through it. Quality product so as expected it had no issues. 

 Came with the 10 round magazine and we bought an additional 20. Comes with everything shown in the photos. Rifle in original box, 1-10 round and 1-20 round magazine. the original stupid cable lock still in its bag. I can't seem to find the manual for it but it is available online. 

 Rifle has been in and out of the safe a few times and out in the woods. Has some small handling marks on it. Most noticeable is a paint scratch on the top of the barrel as seen in the photo. 

 I looked at some of the ar style .22 rifles and have to say this one was in my opinion the best. The weight is substantial. Hold this in one hand and the Mossberg or Colt version in the other and you will see what I mean. This is metal and solid. A great trainer.

 I am looking to trade this more than sell it. I have specific trade desires and am not in a hurry to get rid of this .22. Original receipt in hand shows 649.99 on sale from 750. Too much I know but I really liked it. Now I want a Masterpiece Arms M10 or M11 pistol in 9mm. Would like one with its factory accessories and case if possible but am flexible.

Would meet face to face anywhere between Lynnwood and Arlington Have a preprinted Bill of sale we can fill out for each of our records.

 From Manufacturer:
 The .22 caliber HK 416 is loaded with authentic features. From its appearance, feel, and operation, right down to the sling swivel incorporated into the stock, the 416 D145RS is a replica in every sense.

 Like all the .22 LR H&K's, the 416 is a dedicated .22 rimfire rifle. It is engineered and built in Germany by Carl Walther with a match grade precision barrel, upper and lower metal receivers, a retractable stock, and a machined rail interface system. The 416’s pistol grip and buttstock are authentic in that they include storage compartments for small tools or batteries.

 The magazines for the .22 caliber 416 are made of high-strength polymer and are designed to make loading simple and efficient. They’re available in either a 20- or 10-round version. 

 The .22 caliber HK 416 D145RS operates on a blowback system. The dust cover functions and the bolt holds open when the magazine empties. Its sights are on-rail and the rear sight is adjustable for windage and elevation. Its safety selector rotates 90 degrees from ‘On Safe’ to ‘Fire’. Take down for basic cleaning is simple—there are no loose parts. Just remove the rear receiver pin and pivot the upper receiver to open.

title: For Sale:  Cold Steel Safe Maker I #12BS Push Dagger Self Defense TDI Zombie Knife
postcontent:
Cold Steel Safe Maker I #12BS
Bought this new has sat in my collection. Knife has never cut anything and maintains it's factory razor sharp edge. Comes with awesome secure ex sheath which can be worn on belt or necklace. This is the hard to get 4 1/2 inch blade model.

From Cold Steel:

Cold Steel has been making push knifes for a quarter century. In those twenty five years we have continually been refining our designs, discarding features that didn't perform as well as we would have liked and enhancing those that did. These blades, and the wealth of experience that has gone into their manufacture, have paid off handsomely for Cold Steel as they have generated quite a following among law enforcement and military personnel around the world. This is because they offer "big knife" cutting and piercing potential in a very compact, easily portable size, and, unlike a revolver or semi automatic pistol, they never break, malfunction, or run out of ammunition.
Designed by Lynn C. Thompson, our Safe Make™ push knifes are, without doubt, the finest commercially made push knives in the world. The blade, shaft, and 'T' shaped tang are all drop forged from one piece of AUS 8A Stainless Steel. This process, though costly, eliminates any unwanted sharp edges or surfaces that would irritate the hand or fingers when the knife is clasped in a closed fist, and it produces a better knife, since the subsequent vacuum heat treatment and sub zero quench, renders the blades virtually unbreakable.
Well made blades deserve equally well-made grips. A lot of time and energy went into the production of our 'T' shaped handles. Made of shock absorbing Kray-Ex™ they totally encapsulate the tang and part of the shaft so they can be comfortably and securely grasped in the fist with the blade jutting out between the fingers and used to deliver absolutely devastating punching and slashing blows.
The Safe Maker knives are available in two sizes; each includes an easily concealable and sturdy Secure-Ex® boot/belt sheath. The smaller version includes a steel bead chain lanyard so it can be worn as a neck knife.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Winchester 1885 High Wall Hunter, .325 WSM
postcontent: Recent manufacture Winchester marked model 1885 High Wall chambered for .325 Winchester Short Magnum. The rifle includes a quantity of loaded ammunition (in 150 gr Hornady SP, and 170 gr Hornady RN), a set of full-length reloading dies, a neck-sizing die, a quantity of brass (some once-fired, and some new, never used, all winchester), leupold steel scope bases installed (no rings or optic). The butt-stock is straight grain walnut, and the forearm is figured walnut. The .325 WSM cartridge is adequate for any large game in North America, including the large bears, elk, and moose. The barrel is 28" tapered octagonal factory unit with 4-groove rifling. The extra length gives it some ballistic advantage over a bolt rifle, and reduces muzzle blast and recoil a bit. The 1885 is no longer available in this chambering, and not many were made. If it holds true to the pattern for Winchester rifles, this should make it a collectible rifle, and a solid investment. It is very accurate, and doesn't seem finicky about loads. I have been able to get 1 minute groups or better consistently on paper, and nothing but single-shot kills on game. In all, the rifle is a fine piece, and one of the nicest single-shot drop-blocks on the market. I rate it's condition at 98%, as it has a few very small dings in the finish (not through it, or into the wood) on the butt-stock from bumping into the pommel of my hunting knife while hunting, and some edge wear in the bluing at the muzzle (not noticeable unless you look closely). It is otherwise pristine. I am selling it because it serves no useful purpose to me, and I don't like to keep weapons that gather dust. I love the lines of it, and the history behind the design, but that isn't enough to make me hang on.
